Title:

    esp_price_ticker

Brief:

    This project implements a currency price ticker using an ESP32 module. The
    price information is fetched from a remote API and displayed on a display
    module, regularly.

Notes:

    2026-06-15: As follow-up, I came up with writing an HTTP app module to fetch
    trades and price informations of currency markets from a remote API. I have
    used a linked list to store information for each market. This could be done
    with arrays to but a linked list seemed easier to iterate in a loop and more
    dynamic, in case there is a need to add or remove markets on the fly.
    Currently, one task iterates over the markets and updates the price of each
    market, while a second task displays the fetched data of each market. Since,
    there is a single writer and a single reader for markets, I don't think any
    access control is required for now.

    2026-06-12: I decided to begin the project by adding basic support for an
    SSD1306 display module via I2C bus. The `esp-idf` already has a driver for
    this module in `esp_lcd` component, but the driver seems too overkill for my
    use case, where I only need to display ASCII characters and no scrolling
    stuffs are required. Hence, I decided to write yet another SSD1306 driver.
    This home-made driver is basically adapted from the `i2c_eeprom` component
    from one of the `esp-idf` example projects and worked upon to finally
    support the SSD1306 module. Notably, the driver divides the screen into a
    16x8 grid where each cell can display an 8x8 pixels bitmap. There is also an
    internal buffer that retains all the ASCII character written on the screen
    so far. This `screen_buffer` can be used to optimise write operations by
    eliminating unnecessary rewrites.
